<subSubSection id="C358655E86096B2FFEF68BD6FE19F71A" pageId="27" pageNumber="90" type="description">
<paragraph id="8BFD36D586096B2FFEF68BD6FE19F71A" blockId="27.[253,1238,1908,2592]" pageId="27" pageNumber="90">Definition. A very small, turbiniform gastropod with rounded whorls; protoconch smooth, bulbous; whorls expand rapidly, widely phaneromphalous; ornament a prosocline to orthocline collabral cords with faint spiral threads.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C358655E86096B2FFEF784FCFC63F734" box="[303,1017,2184,2223]" pageId="27" pageNumber="90" type="multiple">
<paragraph id="8BFD36D586096B2FFEF784FCFC63F734" blockId="27.[253,1238,1908,2592]" box="[303,1017,2184,2223]" pageId="27" pageNumber="90">Geological age. Middle or late Visean.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C358655E86096B2FFEF684C3FC1EF690" pageId="27" pageNumber="90" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="8BFD36D586096B2FFEF684C3FC1EF690" blockId="27.[253,1238,1908,2592]" pageId="27" pageNumber="90">Etymology. Referring to the geographical name of the homestead where this genus occurs.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C358655E86096B2FFEF58567FC0EF658" pageId="27" pageNumber="90" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8BFD36D586096B2FFEF58567FC0EF658" blockId="27.[253,1238,1908,2592]" pageId="27" pageNumber="90">
Remarks. 
<taxonomicName id="4C424D5686096B2FFE228567FD21F6A1" authority="Yoo, 1994" authorityName="Yoo" authorityYear="1994" box="[506,699,2323,2362]" class="Gastropoda" family="Elasmonematidae" genus="Kyndalynia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Vetigastropoda" pageId="27" pageNumber="90" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus" status="n.gen.">
<emphasis id="B936EAC786096B2FFE228567FD21F6A1" box="[506,699,2323,2362]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="90">Kyndalynia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A20557BC86096B2FFD028567FCA6F6A1" box="[730,828,2323,2362]" pageId="27" pageNumber="90" rank="genus">n.gen.</taxonomicNameLabel>
is different in shell character from any other described Palaeozoic gastropods. The closest form is 
<emphasis id="B936EAC786096B2FFDB9851BFC95F60E" box="[609,783,2415,2453]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="90">
<taxonomicName id="4C424D5686096B2FFDB9851BFC93F60E" authorityName="Knight" authorityYear="1933" box="[609,777,2415,2453]" class="Gastropoda" family="Eucochlidae" genus="Eucochlis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Vetigastropoda" pageId="27" pageNumber="90" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">Eucochlis</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
but 
<taxonomicName id="4C424D5686096B2FFCBF851BFBB1F60E" authorityName="Yoo" authorityYear="1994" box="[871,1067,2415,2453]" class="Gastropoda" family="Elasmonematidae" genus="Kyndalynia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Vetigastropoda" pageId="27" pageNumber="90" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B936EAC786096B2FFCBF851BFBB1F60E" box="[871,1067,2415,2453]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="90">Kyndalynia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has more inflated whorls and wider umbilicus.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
